<div class="tab-content bg-teal-100 p-6 rounded-lg" id="seasons">
<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-teal-900 mb-4">Adapting the Examen</h2>
  <p class="text-teal-900">
    The Examen is flexible. Whether you're a busy parent, a grieving heart, or a child learning to pray, this practice can meet you where you are.
  </p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-teal-900 mt-4">
    <li><strong>Children:</strong> Use three simple prompts: “What made you smile today?” “What was hard?” “Where was God in that?”</li>
    <li><strong>Busy adults:</strong> Try a two-minute Examen: pause, name one gift from today, one regret, and one hope for tomorrow.</li>
    <li><strong>In grief:</strong> Ask gently, “What did I carry today? What comfort did I notice?”</li>
    <li><strong>For discernment:</strong> Ask, “When did I feel most alive? When did I feel least myself?” These patterns may guide your next step.</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-teal-900 mt-4">
    The Examen doesn’t demand perfection — only honesty and presence. In each season, it becomes a gentle, grounding companion.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="tab-content bg-red-100 p-6 rounded-lg" id="written">
<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-red-900 mb-4">A Prayer in Words</h2>
  <p class="text-red-900 whitespace-pre-line">
    Loving God,

    I pause to breathe, and welcome your light.
    Let me see this day as you saw it — with compassion.

    Thank you for what was kind and good.
    For a task completed, a laugh shared,
    a quiet moment of connection.
    These were your gifts.

    Help me now to look back honestly.
    Where was I stretched?
    Where did I avoid love?
    Where did I show up fully?

    I name what was hard — and I offer it to you.
    I rest not in perfection, but in grace.

    And I look ahead.
    Help me carry forward what I’ve learned.
    Shape my heart for tomorrow.
    Make me ready to walk with you again.

    Amen.
  </p>
</div>
